 times to make mat equal target.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\nn == mat.length == target.length\nn == mat[i].length == target[i].length\n1 <= n <= 10\nmat[i][j] and target[i][j] are either 0 or 1.\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def findRotation(self, mat: List[List[int]], target: List[List[int]]) -> bool:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def findRotation(self, mat: List[List[int]], target: List[List[int]]) -> bool:\n        # Function to rotate the matrix 90 degrees clockwise\n        def rotate(matrix: List[List[int]]) -> List[List[int]]:\n            return [list(reversed(col)) for col in zip(*matrix)]\n        \n        # Check if the matrices are already equal\n        if mat == target:\n            return True\n        \n        # Try rotating the matrix up to 3 times (90, 180, 270 degrees)\n        for _ in range(3):\n            mat = rotate(mat)\n            if mat == target:\n                return True\n        \n        # If no rotation matches the target, return False\n        return False\n```\n\nThis solution defines a helper function `rotate` to perform a 90-degree clockwise rotation on the given matrix. It then checks if the original matrix or any of its rotations (up to 3 times) match the target matrix. If a match is found, it returns `True`; otherwise, it returns `False`.", "estimated_date": 1622937600000}